<div class="title">
<h5>
<a href="/read-only-raspberry-pi">
Read-Only Raspberry Pi<br>
</a> </h5>
<div class="tagline">
<a href="/read-only-raspberry-pi">
Avoid SD card corruption when powering off
</a> </div>
<div class="author">by
<a href="/users/pburgess">
<span class="name">Phillip Burgess</span>
</a> </div>
</div>
</div>
<a href="/read-only-raspberry-pi">
<img src='https://cdn-learn.adafruit.com/guides/images/000/001/794/medium310/unplugged.jpg?1506540302' class='img-responsive guide-image' data-standard-image='https://cdn-learn.adafruit.com/guides/images/000/001/794/medium310/unplugged.jpg?1506540302' data-mobile-image='https://cdn-learn.adafruit.com/guides/images/000/001/794/medium800/unplugged.jpg?1506540302' />
</a> <div class="details">
<div class="description">
<a href="/read-only-raspberry-pi">
Most microcontroller projects have an on/off switch or some quick way to cut power, while computers like the Raspberry Pi require an orderly shutdown procedure…otherwise the SD card may become corrupted and the system will no longer boot.
But what if there was a way?
</a> </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
