<div class="title">
<h5>
<a href="/usb-rechargeable-cordless-soldering-iron">
USB Rechargeable Cordless Soldering Iron<br>
</a> </h5>
<div class="tagline">
<a href="/usb-rechargeable-cordless-soldering-iron">
Hack your Hakko!
</a> </div>
<div class="author">by
<a href="/users/pburgess">
<span class="name">Phillip Burgess</span>
</a> </div>
</div>
</div>
<a href="/usb-rechargeable-cordless-soldering-iron">
<img src='https://cdn-learn.adafruit.com/guides/images/000/001/209/medium310/thumbnail.jpg?1452726501' class='img-responsive guide-image' data-standard-image='https://cdn-learn.adafruit.com/guides/images/000/001/209/medium310/thumbnail.jpg?1452726501' data-mobile-image='https://cdn-learn.adafruit.com/guides/images/000/001/209/medium800/thumbnail.jpg?1452726501' />
</a> <div class="details">
<div class="description">
<a href="/usb-rechargeable-cordless-soldering-iron">
This project takes an existing tool — the Hakko FX-901 cordless soldering iron — and adds USB charging and a beefy Lithium Ion battery inside a 3D-printed pack. I keep this little iron around for cosplay electronics emergencies, and adding USB charging means there’s less to pack…it uses the same phone charger and USB cable I’m already carrying.
</a> </div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
